Date: 2/11/1793
Source: Letter
Author: CAPTAIN RAVEN
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: [? rimu] She [a ship built in Dusky Bay] is planked, decked, and ceiled with the spruce fir, which in the opinion of the carpenter is very little inferior to English oak. There are various kinds of timber in Dusky Bay, but that which is principally fit for shipbuilding is the spruce fir, which may be cut along the shore in any quantity or size for the construction of vessels from a first-rate to a small wherry. ...[179] Tea they made from the spruce and tea-trees.
Notes: 1793 Nov 2 CAPTAIN RAVEN to Lieutenant-Governor King in 1908 McNab Historical Records I/178, 179

Date: 0/0/1817
Source: New Zealand (various authors/titles)
Author: NICHOLAS
Vol / Page: 2/247
Edition:
Quote: Of the other trees noticed by Capt. Cook ... is one resembling the American spruce fir, and from the leaves of which a very wholesome liquor was brewed. This was called the New Zealand spruce fir, from its similarity to the former tree, ... growing to a great height, with long pendant branches, covered with articulated leaves in a flourishing state of verdure.
